ically tricky literature created the perfect grounds for puzzlement and partial comprehension. Through the lens of a history of imperfect reading, we see that many of the period’s major works—by writers including Daniel Defoe, Eliza Haywood, Mary Wortley Montagu, Alexander Pope and Jonathan Swift—both generated and depended upon widespread misreading. Being foxed by a satire, coded fiction or allegory was, like Wordle or the cryptic crossword, a form of entertainment, and perhaps a group sport. Rather than worrying that we don’t have all the answers, we should instead recognize the cultural importance of not knowing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBooks and readingzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aEnglish literaturexAppreciation. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSatire, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 18th Century .2bisacsh  aAbigail Williams.  aAlexander Pope.  aAlternative History.  aAmerican Literature.  aBritish Literature.  aDaniel Defoe.  aEarly Eighteenth-Century Literature.  aEliza Haywood.  aJonathan Swift.  aMary Wortley Montagu.  aReading It Wrong: An Alternative History of Early Eighteenth-Century Literature.  acritical analysis.  acultural importance of not knowing.  aeighteenth-century literature.  afantastically tricky literature.  afiction.  aflawed interpretation has its own history.  agolden age of satire.  ahistory.  ahow we read.  aimperfect reading.  ajottings of readers.  aliterature.  amarginal marks.  amisinterpretation of eighteenth-century literature.  aprinceton university press.  aquirky.  asocial life of books.  athe importance of interpretation.  athrough the lens of a history of imperfect reading.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Uni